04772nam a22006255i 9780774854757DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20071996xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748547577 a10.59962/97807748547572doi  a(DE-B1597)662285  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV8693.Q34 1996eb 7aLAW0600002bisacsh04a364.600aQualities of Mercy :bJustice, Punishment, and Discretion /ced. by Carolyn Strange. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (198 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCivilized People Don’t Want to See That Kind of Thing: The Decline of Public Physical Punishment in London, 1760-1840 -- tIn Place of Death: Transportation, Penal Practices, and the English State, 1770-1830 -- t‘Harshness and Forbearance’: The Politics of Pardons and the Upper Canada Rebellion -- tSavage Mercy: Native Culture and the Modification of Capital Punishment in Nineteenth-Century British Columbia -- tDiscretionary Justice: Political Culture and the Death Penalty in New South Wales and Ontario, 1890-1920 -- tPunishment in Late-Twentieth-Century Canada: An Afterword -- tSelect Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aQualities of Mercy deals with the history of mercy, the remittance of punishments in the criminal law. The writers probe the discretionary use of power and inquire how it has been exercised to spare convicted criminals from the full might of the law. Drawing on the history of England, Canada, and Australia in periods when both capital and corporal punishment were still practised, they show that contrary to common assumptions the past was not a time of unmitigated terror and they ask what inspired restraint in punishment. They conclude that the ability to decide who lived and died -- through the exercise or denial of mercy -- reinforced the power structure. The essays are an important contribution to current public policy debates. If today's move towards unyielding and harsher punishment proceeds, including campaigns to reinstate capital punishment, mercy alone will fail to neutralize the inequities of criminal justice. Only profound cultural shifts and transitions of sensibility have the force to stem the tide of unprecedented punitiveness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPunishmentzAustraliaxHistory. 0aPunishmentzCanadaxHistory. 0aPunishmentzGreat BritainxHistory. 7aLAW / Legal History.2bisacsh1 aDevereaux, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoob, Anthony N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoo, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Greg T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrange, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrange, Carolyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWright, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485475740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774854757423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774854757/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11